In the https://github.com/flutter/plugins/blob/master/packages/video_player/lib/video_player.dart video player plugin I send an "init" message in the initializer of the field holding the MessageChannel to the plugin.
```dart
final MethodChannel _channel = const MethodChannel('flutter.io/videoPlayer')
  // This will clear all open videos on the platform when a full restart is
  // performed.
  ..invokeMethod("init");
```

When the plugin receives the "init" message it resets its state.
```java
  switch (call.method) {
      case "init":
        for (VideoPlayer player : videoPlayers.values()) {
          player.dispose();
        }
        videoPlayers.clear();
        break;
```

 I believe this pattern could work for the keyboard as well.

@matthew-carroll I do the following in `main`, before `runApp`, and it seems to correctly close the on-screen keyboard on app hot restart.

```dart
  SystemChannels.textInput.invokeMethod('TextInput.hide');
```

> Is anyone against me just calling SystemChannels.textInput.invokeMethod('TextInput.hide');

I believe this issue is broader than just invoking a system channel 

cc: @cbracken for your input

